[3] Pakistan, another violence episode
Date: Thu 25 Apr 2019
Source: Yeni Safak [edited]
https://www.yenisafak.com/en/world/gunman-kills-anti-polio-vaccinator-in-sw-pakistan-3479797


A female anti-polio vaccinator was gunned down and another injured on Thursday [25 Apr 2019] in southwestern Pakistan, local media reported.

The incident -- the latest in a series of similar attacks -- took place in a remote town of Chaman near the Afghanistan border when the immunization team were vaccinating the children against the infectious polio disease, the local broadcaster Geo News said. The recent attack forced the authorities to suspend the ongoing vaccination effort in the region, it added.

It was the 3rd incident of targeting polio workers or the personnel providing security to the vaccinators in less than a week. The previous 2 incidents -- which left 2 police in charge of the security of the vaccinators dead -- were reported in the northwestern Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KP) province.

No group has yet claimed responsibility for the attack; however, suspicion is focusing on the outlawed Pakistani Taliban, which have been involved in similar attacks during a decade.

The latest attack came days after 2 new cases of polio virus were reported in Pakistan.

With the new cases, reported in the Bannu and North Waziristan districts of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province, the total number of polio cases reported in the country has risen to 8 since the beginning of this year [2019].

Six polio cases were reported in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KP) and tribal districts, while one case was reported in each of the Punjab and Sindh provinces.

Pakistan is among 3 countries in the world, including Afghanistan and Nigeria, where polio virus still exists, and the country remains under a polio-linked travel restriction imposed by the World Health Organization (WHO). In 2014, the WHO made it mandatory for all people traveling from Pakistan to carry a polio vaccination certificate.

Armed assailants targeting vaccinators see the anti-polio campaigns as part of an elaborate anti-Muslim and Western conspiracy, and often issue death threats to vaccinators, many of whom are women, for administrating the vital vaccines to children.

According to Pakistani officials, around 88 people associated with the drive have been killed across Pakistan since December 2012.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Chaman is a town northwest of Quetta in Boluchistan province, on the border with Afghanistan (for a map showing provinces and major towns in Pakistan, see https://logofmaps.files.wordpress.com/2015/10/pakistan-map-1.jpg. The 2 other fatal attacks occurred in the northern province of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. All 3 attacks occurred in areas with known civil unrest, and areas with known WPV circulation from either confirmed cases or environmental samples. - Mod.MPP]

******
[4] Afghanistan, (WHO/ICRC banned)
Date: Sat 13 Apr 2019
Source: TOLO News [edited]
https://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/icrc-who%C2%A0halt%C2%A0activities-due%C2%A0-taliban%E2%80%99s-threat


The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) and the World Health Organization (WHO) have stopped their activities in Afghanistan as they have been threatened by the Taliban, officials of the 2 organizations confirmed.

Taliban in a statement on Friday [12 Apr 2019] announced that the ICRC and WHO cannot operate in the areas under their influence until further notice. The group said the 2 organizations have not put into practice the commitments they made to the group.

WHO warns that the Taliban's move will put negative impacts on healthcare services of the organization to vulnerable people in Afghanistan.

Tarik Jasarevic, a spokesman of WHO said they are worried about the banning of their activities, insisting that they want all the warring parties to maintain security of healthcare personnel.

"Obviously, we are concerned that this will negatively impact delivery of health services to the affected population. We know that unhindered access to all areas is necessary to provide health services to those in need," said Jasarevic.

Officials from the ICRC, meanwhile, said they are in talks with the Taliban to resolve the problem and resume activities.

Afghanistan's Ministry of Interior said the Afghan security forces are committed to ensuring the safety of the ICRC and WHO staff members.

"The ICRC is a charity and impartial organization, but the enemy of the Afghan people once again proved that they ban all the humanitarian and charity activities. We will always cooperate with them in maintaining their security," the Interior Ministry spokesman Nusrat Rahimi said.

The ICRC has operated in Afghanistan over the past 30 years, and the committees' activities are mostly focused on providing assistance to war prisoners and war victims.

The WHO provides polio vaccination services to children as well as other healthcare services to Afghans around the country.

[Byline: Karim Amini]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In searching for another article on the Taliban being against polio vaccination in Afghanistan, I found the above article reviewing the recent WHO and ICRC ban by the Taliban. In another article, there is a discussion that says more than 1 million children were deprived of vaccinations during 2018 as a result of Taliban and Islamic State [IS] militants interfering with and barring polio vaccination activities in some regions in the country (see https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/official-taliban-deprive-afghan-kids-polio-vaccine for more detail).

Given the challenges confronting countries with political unrest and the inability to find rational individuals who will permit sound public health actions to protect the populations, one can't help but wonder if a goal of disease eradication is feasible under these conditions. Add to this (and I am very much risking condemnation from some colleagues working in the polio eradication initiative) the recurrent appearance of cVDPVs in multiple countries around the world -- in the past 12 months, cVDPV-associated polio cases and positive environmental samples have been reported from 7 countries (see section [1] for more details) -- I can't help but wonder if the time has come for total cessation of use of the oral poliovirus vaccines (mOPV, bOPV, and tOPV), or we will continue to chase after cVDPVs trying to interrupt transmission of all polioviruses worldwide. - Mod.MPP]
